The main result here is `CliffordAlgebra (Q‚ÇÅ.prod Q‚ÇÇ) ‚âÉ‚Çê[R] (evenOdd Q‚ÇÅ ·µç‚äó[R] evenOdd Q‚ÇÇ)`.

The proof of `map_inl_mul_map_inr_of_mem_evenOdd` is rather ugly here, but I suspect to pull off an `ext`-based proof, we need a bunch of missing infrastructure:
* Morphisms of graded algebras
* The tensor product of graded algebras *as a graded algebra*

I think it's probably worth singling out these corollaries:
```suggestion

variable (m‚ÇÅ : CliffordAlgebra Q‚ÇÅ) (m‚ÇÇ : CliffordAlgebra Q‚ÇÇ)

theorem Commute_map_inl_inr_of_mem_evenOdd_zero_left {i : ZMod 2}
     (hm‚ÇÅ : m‚ÇÅ ‚àà evenOdd Q‚ÇÅ 0) (hm‚ÇÇ : m‚ÇÇ ‚àà evenOdd Q‚ÇÇ i) :
    Commute (map (.inl Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÅ) (map (.inr Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÇ) :=
  show _ * _ = _ * _ from by simp [map_inl_mul_map_inr_of_mem_evenOdd _ _ _ hm‚ÇÅ _ hm‚ÇÇ]

theorem Commute_map_inl_inr_of_mem_evenOdd_zero_right {i : ZMod 2}
    (hm‚ÇÅ : m‚ÇÅ ‚àà evenOdd Q‚ÇÅ i) (hm‚ÇÇ : m‚ÇÇ ‚àà evenOdd Q‚ÇÇ 0) :
    Commute (map (.inl Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÅ) (map (.inr Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÇ) :=
  show _ * _ = _ * _ from by simp [map_inl_mul_map_inr_of_mem_evenOdd _ _ _ hm‚ÇÅ _ hm‚ÇÇ]

theorem map_inl_mul_map_inr_eq_neg_of_mem_evenOdd_one
    (hm‚ÇÅ : m‚ÇÅ ‚àà evenOdd Q‚ÇÅ 1) (hm‚ÇÇ : m‚ÇÇ ‚àà evenOdd Q‚ÇÇ 1) :
    (map (.inl Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÅ) * (map (.inr Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÇ) =
    - (map (.inr Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÇ) * (map (.inl Q‚ÇÅ Q‚ÇÇ) m‚ÇÅ) := by
  simp [map_inl_mul_map_inr_of_mem_evenOdd _ _ _ hm‚ÇÅ _ hm‚ÇÇ]

```

I ended up generalizing the statement away from `inl` and `inr`, but added analogous versions of your lemmas.

Perhaps in future we needed a `GradedCommute` helper to handle this family of lemmas automatically...

```suggestion

## TODO:

Introduce morphisms and equivalences of graded algebas and upgrade `CliffordAlgebra.equivProd` to a
graded algebra equivalence.

```

How about:
```suggestion
      simp_rw [LinearMap.coprod_apply, LinearMap.coe_comp, Function.comp_apply,
        AlgHom.toLinearMap_apply, QuadraticForm.prod_apply, Submodule.coeSubtype,
        GradedTensorProduct.includeLeft_apply, GradedTensorProduct.includeRight_apply, map_add,
        add_mul, mul_add, GradedTensorProduct.algebraMap_def,
        GradedTensorProduct.tmul_one_mul_one_tmul, GradedTensorProduct.tmul_one_mul_coe_tmul,
        GradedTensorProduct.tmul_coe_mul_one_tmul, GradedTensorProduct.tmul_coe_mul_coe_tmul,
        LinearMap.codRestrict_apply, one_mul, uzpow_one, Units.neg_smul, one_smul, Œπ_sq_scalar,
        mul_one, ‚Üê GradedTensorProduct.algebraMap_def, ‚Üê GradedTensorProduct.algebraMap_def']
```
(presumably previously not possible because of now extinct shortcomings of `simp`)
Sure, why not! I think I was trying to structure the proof a bit more, but upon re-reading I can't see what I was going for anyway.

Nitpick: we have `m‚ÇÅ : M‚ÇÇ` in the second goal.
```suggestion
  ext m <;> dsimp
```
Also: shouldn't we squeeze that `dsimp`?
I don't think we usually bother squeezing `dsimp`s unless they are slow.

I prefer
```suggestion
We show that the Clifford algebra of a direct sum is the graded tensor product of the Clifford
```
but I don't insist

as above
```suggestion
/-- The Clifford algebra over an orthogonal direct sum of quadratic vector spaces is isomorphic
as an algebra to the graded tensor product of the Clifford algebras of each space.
```
Weirdly, after lifting things to `variable`, I now have to use `nonrec` here to avoid an error later on!
